# Data-Format Contracts (REMI App ↔ REMI Backend)

This rule codifies the few format contracts where producer/consumer
disagreement has historically caused user-visible bugs (calendar drift,
events disappearing, invisible shares). Sections grow as new
contracts get burned by experience — keep this file the canonical
list, don't re-invent helpers per-call-site.

---

## 1. Datetime: backend `timestamptz` columns

### The contract

Strings sent to a Postgres `timestamptz` column (e.g.
`personal_events.start_time`, `personal_events.end_time`,
`appointments.cancelled_at`) MUST be fully-qualified ISO 8601 with an
explicit timezone marker — either `Z` for UTC or `±HH:MM` for an
offset.

Strings without a TZ marker (e.g. `"2026-04-21T09:00:00"`) are
**ambiguous**. Postgres `timestamptz` interprets them using the
session timezone (UTC on Render and most cloud Postgres deployments),
which silently shifts the stored value by the user's UTC offset on
ingestion. Round-trip the value and the calendar drifts by 4–5 hours.

### The only sanctioned producer / parsers

Three helpers, one per consumption mode. Pick by what you need:

```ts
import {
  localToBackendISO,           // form → backend (producer)
  backendISOToLocalParts,      // backend → form fields (parser)
  backendISOToLocalMinutes,    // backend → grid Y-coordinate (parser)
} from "@/src/utils/datetime";

// Form submit (date + time captured as user's local wall-clock):
start_time: localToBackendISO(date, startTime),  // "2026-04-21T09:00:00-04:00"

// Form prefill (backend returned a fully-qualified ISO):
const { date, time } = backendISOToLocalParts(event.start_time);

// Calendar grid placement (need minutes-of-day for from/to):
const from = backendISOToLocalMinutes(pe.start_time);  // local minutes
const to   = backendISOToLocalMinutes(pe.end_time);
```

### Anti-patterns — DO NOT

```ts
// Producer side (form → backend):
start_time: `${date}T${startTime}:00`,           // no TZ marker → drift
start_time: new Date(`${date}T${time}`).toISOString(), // also drift; toISOString() emits Z but the input was parsed as local first

// Parser side (backend → form fields):
setStartTime(event.start_time.slice(0, 5));      // returns "2026-" because the field is a full ISO, not "HH:MM:SS"

// Parser side (backend → grid Y-coordinate):
const tail = pe.start_time.split("T").pop();     // "10:00:00.000Z"
const minutes = parseInt(tail.slice(0, 2), 10) * 60 + ...;  // returns UTC minutes; event renders 4 hours off in EDT
timeStringToMinutes(pe.start_time);              // SAME BUG — slices and ignores the `Z`. Reserved for TZ-naive `appointments.scheduled_time` only.
```

`timeStringToMinutes` and similar local helpers in
`resource-calendar-mapping.ts` and `LandscapeWorkweekView.tsx` are
guarded with a `__DEV__` warning that fires when given a TZ-aware
input, so this anti-pattern is loud-failing at run time. Don't
suppress the warning — fix the call site to use
`backendISOToLocalMinutes`.

### Why the asymmetry between personal events and appointments

`appointments.scheduled_date` is `DATE` and `appointments.scheduled_time`
is `TIME` — both timezone-naive, so the naive string-build pattern
happens to be harmless there. `personal_events.start_time/end_time` are
`timestamptz`, so the same pattern silently corrupts the data. The
column type is what makes this a contract violation, not the producer
shape. Don't assume "appointments work, so personal events should too."

### History

- 2026-04-21 dev-log entry: "Personal Event Times Off-By-UTC-Offset —
  Datetime Contract Fix". Before this rule existed, this bug was
  introduced AND a related edit-prefill bug shipped together because
  there was no canonical helper to point reviewers at.
- 2026-04-21 dev-log entry (same day, second pass): "Personal Event
  Placement Off-By-UTC-Offset — Consumer-Side Datetime Fix". The
  producer fix above made round-trip storage correct, but the calendar
  mapper (`resource-calendar-mapping.ts` and `LandscapeWorkweekView.tsx`)
  still sliced the time portion off the backend ISO string and treated
  it as local time → grid placement was 4 hours off. Same column-type
  asymmetry, opposite end of the wire. The first version of this rule
  only covered the producer side; consumer side added in the follow-up
  fix. Lesson: when you see a `timestamptz` ⇄ TZ-naive column-type
  mismatch in one direction, check the other direction in the SAME PR.

